40abb4f7d73ceadf087e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c41ab4521c4c2b6bde7b03ec4d9531acdc101f7e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a545f286136f5024bdadaa47d305e437cf32614f.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" sequential workflow steps includes:\n \n numbering of each step (0100, 0200, 0250, etc.) \n the action (LoadData, StoreData, Transform, etc.) \n the related Entity or Data store (here \u201CTask\u201D) \n \n \n Error Handling is set to  WorkflowFails  on  OnFailure , which stops the workflow if any error occurs. \n  OutputContextStore  is set to one of the existing Context stores in the workflow ( Task  here). \n  OutputMethod  determines how data is written to the output Context store (here  AppendMergeExisting  that appends new data to existing content;  FullMerge  would clear existing content and then write new data, more about merge types is  here ). \n  Service  \u2013 to load existing data, you need to use  DataService . \n  ServiceMethod  \u2013 for loading data, use the  LoadData  method. \n  Roles  \u2013 we keep the workflow available to all users using the asterisk symbol. \n  TraceLevel  \u2013 we use the same level as set for the whole workflow. \n \n   Step 2: Select tasks \n Once all existing tasks are loaded into the Context store, we need to display them to the user and allow them to select which tasks to reassign. \n For this purpose, right-click on the first task, select  Add After  and create a new workflow step of type  (Task) User Interface : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/9/92d6864a25be6fc5aac2f93ca35bedaa795587f0.png]\nDescription: The image displays a flowchart titled \u0022TakeOverTasks\u0022 with a clear start (green circle) and end (red circle) point. Within the flowchart, there is a task labeled \u00220100_LoadData_Task\u0022 which includes three components: \u0022DataStructure,\u0022 \u0022Task,\u0022 and \u0022Parameters.\u0022 A context menu is shown with options including \u0022Delete,\u0022 \u0022New,\u0022 and \u0022Add After.\u0022 The submenu options under \u0022Add After\u0022 consist of various tasks such as \u0022(Task) User Interface,\u0022 \u0022(Task) Service Method Call,\u0022 and other workflow-related actions. The visible elements suggest this interface is for managing tasks within a workflow system or an automation tool.\n\n\n  \n Configure it as follows: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/bafed8929b25ca7ac698a94f6c87f8e62c0b0737.png]\nDescription: The image presents a user interface titled \u00220200_SelectionUI_Task\u0022 associated with a schema item, displaying detailed configuration options. Visible sections include \u0022Data Refresh Parameters\u0022 with fields such as \u0022RefreshDataStructure,\u0022 \u0022RefreshMethod,\u0022 and \u0022RefreshSortSet.\u0022 The \u0022Error Handling\u0022 section specifies \u0022OnFailure\u0022 as \u0022WorkflowFails.\u0022 Under \u0022Misc,\u0022 parameters like \u0022AutoNext,\u0022 \u0022IsFinalForm,\u0022 and \u0022IsRefreshSuppressedBeforeFirstSave\u0022 are listed, with specific values displayed. The \u0022OutputMethod\u0022 field indicates \u0022FullMerge,\u0022 while rules and save parameters are outlined, including \u0022AllowSave\u0022 set to false and various rule context stores. The interface appears designed for configuring task-related settings within a software application.\n\n\n  \n Notes: \n \n  IsFinalForm  is set to  False  because this is not the last step of the workflow. \n  OutputMethod  is set to  FullMerge , this is the default setup for a user interface task. \n  Screen  is set to  Task , reusing the existing Task screen as a list view. Checkboxes will be added later. \n  AllowSave  is set to  False , as we do not want to display the standard Save button in the workflow screen. Changes will be saved in the following steps. \n \n Now the second step is added to the workflow schema: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ef9897b6da00b17e4aca632b932176a8a2e8ddd6.png]\nDescription: The image presents a flowchart titled \u0022TakeOverTasks,\u0022 illustrating a sequence of tasks. It begins with a green \u0022Start\u0022 node leading to \u00220100_LoadData_Task,\u0022 followed by an arrow directing to \u00220200_SelectionUI_Task,\u0022 which is depicted in a rectangular box. The flow subsequently connects to a red \u0022End\u0022 node, indicating the termination of the task sequence. In the upper right corner, there is a button labeled \u0022Task.\u0022 The overall purpose of the diagram is to outline the workflow and progression between the tasks involved in the TakeOverTasks process.\n\n\n  \n Note that a new element named  Dependencies  is created in the Model Browser. It defines the sequence in which the workflow steps are executed: \n  \n\n","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-02T00:02:37"},"vector":[-0.029210726,-0.0059672417,-0.06652726,0.030874604,0.019127255,0.011257151,0.013912134,0.01711959,-0.0048670596,0.016563063,-0.0005111656,-0.013006364,0.014326083,0.012206351,0.019455867,-0.023241213,-0.024648735,-0.016215548,0.027962724,0.0055119293,0.03913581,-0.012301059,0.026883747,0.03921372,0.009748644,0.047571655,0.0011431384,-0.039484676,-0.037452474,0.017500905,-0.00850154,-0.02329786,-0.022187402,-0.02465355,-0.009918426,-0.016013633,-0.006668122,-0.013550766,-0.035954908,0.015307553,0.0012597443,-0.004184428,0.011200331,-0.0015336846,0.030165335,-0.03110563,-0.027691955,-0.011002583,-0.0061545717,-0.0748114,-0.03535102,-0.031841297,0.021433976,-0.036056153,0.033346355,0.037022095,-0.038959138,-0.030987322,-0.08958994,0.027081678,-0.037843045,0.009169415,-0.0014963745,0.004699013,-0.005109289,0.021145213,-0.028074373,0.01932058,-0.0110088,-0.028431125,0.04342686,0.036451038